      <h2>Extended email marketing playbook for food and beverage brands</h2>
      <p>This section is the retention magazine view of food and beverage brands: not which app has the prettiest templates, but which inbox moments actually move repeat purchase when repeat purchase windows, subscriptions, and limited-time flavors dominate operations.</p>
      <p>Start with consent archaeology. Map every popup, checkout, footer, SMS keyword, and partner import that feeds email. food and beverage brands often fail when giveaway subscribers receive the same welcome as high-intent product-page signups.</p>
      <p>Week-one deliverable: welcome segmented by source with suppressions for existing customers, recent purchasers, and employees. If your current tool cannot branch on signup source, that is the selection constraint — not missing AI copy features.</p>
      <p>Week-two deliverable: one recovery flow with inventory checks and discount caps documented. food and beverage brands lose margin when cart recovery treats a $35 accessory and a $350 bundle identically.</p>
      <p>Week-three deliverable: post-purchase education tied to 1–4 week consumption; subscription-heavy; limited sku availability. The email should reduce support tickets and set up the next purchase — not only ask for a review on day one.</p>
      <p>Week-four deliverable: replenishment or winback with VIP exclusions. Track Reorder rate by product and Subscription skip recovery against Shopify net sales, not only ESP attribution.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy ranks first in our food and beverage brands shortlist because agent-first playbooks compress those four weeks for lean teams. Klaviyo wins when someone owns predictive segments weekly. Omnisend wins when SMS must ship beside email immediately.</p>
      <p>Pricing discipline: model 90-day sends, not 90-day profiles. food and beverage brands with wide lists and narrow engagement punish per-contact billing — pay-per-email alternatives reward pruning and targeting.</p>
      <p>Sale-week governance: document which flows pause when site-wide promos run. Collision between welcome, cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and campaign blasts is the silent LTV killer for food and beverage brands.</p>
      <p>Deliverability preflight before peak season: SPF, DKIM, DMARC alignment, popup-offer match, sunset policies for 180-day inactives, and seedlist tests across Gmail and Apple Mail.</p>
      <p>When leaving a legacy sender, export consent timestamps and parallel-run critical flows two weeks. Attribution debates slow adoption more than template rebuilds.</p>
      <p>Final operator rule for food and beverage brands: email should feel like the store remembering the customer — product context, timing respect, and margin honesty. Pick the app your team will tune every Monday.</p>
      <p>Use the comparison hub when torn between two finalists — workflow tests beat feature matrices. Use use-case playbooks for trigger, timing, and exclusion detail on welcome, cart, post-purchase, and winback.</p>
      <p>If you only fix one thing this quarter for food and beverage brands, fix suppression logic. Recent buyers, VIPs, wholesale accounts, and gift purchasers should not receive stranger-discount language — that single change often lifts placement and LTV more than a new template pack.</p>
